Chocolate Eclair was too sweet no flavor.  Strawberry Coke was too dry and too sweet.  Quiche was good. Croissant was good.  Cappuccino was warm (room temperature)and dull espresso taste. Fantastic place. We just visited this shop for the first time and it was such a good experience. The employee that greeted us, I think the owner, came out from the counter to introduce herself to our 1-year-old who was all smiles with her. She then proceeded to take our order and show us all kinds of kindness. The service was worth 5 stars all on its own, but then we come to the atmosphere of the cafe - awesome. It was clean, open, and inviting. On top of all this, my Vanilla Latte was one of the best I've ever had (and I've had a lot). My wife also LOVED her Vanilla Cappuccino. We had such a great experience that we're going to make sure to visit every time we're in DC.

Amazing and exquisite bakery and sandwiches. I had to ask for the name of the manager as they were so down to earth and pleasant. Ionela is cheerful this is the place to start your day! Going home with my fresh, warm, and individually wrapped baguette

Basically whoever is managing this location this morning allows vagrancy at their door. A man approached us about money outside blocking our way in. I calmly told him we didn’t have any to give in which he retorted with threats and obscenities. When I have money im more than generous to our communities under served and unfortunate. Upon hearing his nasty words to my partner I became very upset and was very vocal when walking in. The sitting manager who wasn’t wearing a mask scrambled and stood up putting on her mask while her fellow employees at the table sat there looking at me like I was crazy. The manager said she couldn’t do anything about the man who was blocking the door and had items sitting on outside tables. In an attempt to walk away from the situation and calm down the manager didn’t reassure me. She said she couldn’t do anything unless the man was inside even though he was right at the door and using a table outside filled with his items. Rather than deal with the situation properly this manager threatened to call the police on both of us. Both. I am a long time customer of Paul both in dc and Paris and quite frankly I am appalled at how this situation was handled. I did nothing to harm anyone even though I was visibly upset. The man tried to come back in the store at which point my partner was so overwhelmed and hadn’t even been allowed to order that she had to leave the situation. The man cursed at her as she walked out the door and continued to curse at me. The manager asked me to leave and I did. I left hungry and frustrated feeing like my pleas were unheard and my European bakery experience ruined. Never in my life have I ever talked down to someone less fortunate than myself and somehow this man was allowed to make us feel unsafe because we didn’t have money for him. Sad to say I will never be a customer at Paul Bakery ever again. When I left the employees went back too crowding their table, maskless, and laughing at my misfortune.

We stopped in yesterday for lunch (around 11:45AM) with a group of 6. All of their sandwiches are pre-made and on display; a lot like Devon & Blakley. Although when I made the comparison, my coworker said that Paul is better than D&B. I agree in terms of the bread--it was the highlight of my sandwich, for sure. I got the Dieppois sandwich and I would say it was just average for me. The filling was not seasoned well, if at all.  There was also some confusion when we placed our orders. When the guy taking our order asked if we wanted our sandwich toasted, most of the group said yes. I, thankfully, did not. He warned us that it could take up to 8 minutes, which wasn't really a big deal. He appeared to be taking sandwiches out of the display to warm up, but another employee (in hushed/muffled tones, mind you) told him that we needed to order our sandwich at the counter since they couldn't remove toppings (i.e. lettuce, tomatoes) to warm them up. However, they never made that clear to my cohorts. I just happened to hear them and told some of our group who had assumed their sandwich was already warming in the oven.  They got one order completely wrong and another person in our party had to wait a lot longer than 8 minutes to get his food.  There are clearly some kinks and communication issues that need to be addressed, but lunch at Paul was not a total bust. The saving grace and highlight of lunch was the sweet treat I picked up alongside my sandwich. Flaky, buttery puff pastry filled with an amaretto cream. YUM.
